<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1437,1867,2036]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1867,1892]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body elongate-oval. Tarsi short, tarsomere 3 subcordate and slightly wider than tarsomere 2. Penis body robust, with one pair of elongate sclerotized plates, up-turned at base and covering orifice (char. 79.4), movable (char. 80.1), and with ventral median vermiform sclerite (char. 81.1) only visible when plate is opened. Endophallus with W-shaped sclerite complex basally articulate (char. 84.4), entwined by membranous saccule with many very small spicules and open dorsally (char. 88.1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,151,176]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Remarks.</emphasis>
This monospecific group, presently composed only of 
<taxonomicName box="[948,1060,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Bagous" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutosus">
<emphasis box="[948,1060,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">B. lutosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species widespread in Europe and western and central Asia, is easily distinguishable from all other Bagoini by the unique characters of the sclerites of the penis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,151,285]" box="[199,870,260,285]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
